Guided Exercise: Resource Manifests
Goal
Deploy and update an application using YAML files stored in a Git repository.
This demonstrates a real production workflow:
Git repository → YAML manifests → OpenShift cluster
________________________________________
What You Learn in This Exercise
1.	Deploy application using YAML manifests from Git
2.	Validate manifests before deployment
3.	Compare changes between versions
4.	Update applications using new manifests
5.	Restart pods when configuration changes
________________________________________
Step 1: Start the Lab Environment
Command:
lab start declarative-manifests
What this does
This command prepares the environment:
•	resets cluster resources
•	prepares the Git repository
•	creates required directories
•	ensures the exercise environment is clean
________________________________________
Step 2: Login to OpenShift Cluster
Command:
oc login -u developer -p developer https://api.ocp4.example.com:6443
Explanation
Part	Meaning
oc	OpenShift CLI
login	Authenticate to cluster
-u developer	username
-p developer	password
URL	API server address
Output:
Login successful
Now the user can manage resources.
________________________________________
Step 3: Create a New Project
Command:
oc new-project declarative-manifests
What this does
Creates a namespace/project for this application.
Projects isolate resources.
Result:
Now using project declarative-manifests
All resources will be deployed inside this namespace.
________________________________________
Step 4: Clone the Git Repository
Move to labs directory:
cd ~/DO280/labs
Clone repository:
git clone https://git.ocp4.example.com/developer/declarative-manifests.git
What this does
Downloads application manifests stored in Git.
Directory structure:
declarative-manifests
   database.yaml
   exoplanets.yaml
These YAML files define the application.
________________________________________
Step 5: Inspect Repository Contents
Command:
ls -lA
Output:
database.yaml
exoplanets.yaml
Meaning
File	Purpose
database.yaml	Database resources
exoplanets.yaml	Application resources
Resources defined inside may include:
•	ConfigMap
•	Secret
•	Deployment
•	Service
•	Route
________________________________________
Step 6: Check Git Versions
Command:
git log --oneline
Output shows versions:
v1.0
v1.1.0
v1.1.1
These represent application versions.
Version	Description
v1.0	first release
v1.1.0	second release
v1.1.1	third release
This is a GitOps workflow where app versions are stored in Git.
________________________________________
Step 7: Deploy First Application Version
Switch to version v1.0:
git checkout v1.0
This loads the first version manifests.
________________________________________
Step 8: Validate YAML Before Deployment
Command:
oc apply -f . --validate=true --dry-run=server -n declarative-manifests
Explanation
Option	Meaning
-f .	apply all YAML files in current directory
--validate=true	validate YAML syntax
--dry-run=server	test without applying
-n	namespace
Output example:
deployment.apps/database created (server dry run)
Important: No resource is actually created.
This prevents errors before deployment.
________________________________________
Step 9: Deploy the Application
Command:
oc apply -f . --namespace declarative-manifests
This creates all resources.
Example output:
configmap/database created
secret/database created
deployment.apps/database created
service/database created
deployment.apps/exoplanets created
route.route.openshift.io/exoplanets created
________________________________________
Resources Created
The application includes:
Resource	Purpose
ConfigMap	configuration values
Secret	sensitive data
Deployment	manages pods
Service	exposes pods internally
Route	exposes application externally
________________________________________
Step 10: Monitor Pods
Command:
watch oc get deployments,pods --namespace declarative-manifests
What this does
Continuously shows pod status.
Example output:
deployment.apps/database
deployment.apps/exoplanets

pod/database-xxxx Running
pod/exoplanets-xxxx Running
Important concept:
The exoplanets pod may temporarily crash if the database is not ready yet.
________________________________________
Step 11: Check Application Route
Command:
oc get routes -l app=exoplanets -n declarative-manifests
Output:
exoplanets.apps.ocp4.example.com
This URL allows external access.
Opening it in a browser shows application version v1.0.
________________________________________
Step 12: Deploy Second Version (v1.1.0)
Switch version:
git checkout v1.1.0
Now YAML files contain updated manifests.
________________________________________
Step 13: Compare Manifest Changes
Command:
oc diff -f . --namespace declarative-manifests
Output example:
- image: exoplanets:v1.0
+ image: exoplanets:v1.1.0
Meaning:
The container image version changed.
This will trigger a new deployment rollout.
________________________________________
Step 14: Apply the Update
Command:
oc apply -f . --namespace declarative-manifests
Output:
deployment.apps/exoplanets configured
Now Kubernetes performs a rolling update.
New pods replace old ones.
________________________________________
Step 15: Monitor Pods Again
Command:
watch oc get deployments,pods
New pod example:
exoplanets-74c85f5796 Running
This confirms version v1.1.0 is running.
________________________________________
Step 16: Deploy Third Version (v1.1.1)
Switch version:
git checkout v1.1.1
________________________________________
Step 17: Compare Changes
Command:
oc diff -f .
Output:
Secret updated
DB_USER changed
This means the database credentials changed.
________________________________________
Step 18: Apply the Update
Command:
oc apply -f . --namespace declarative-manifests
But notice:
deployment.apps/exoplanets unchanged
Meaning:
Pods are not recreated automatically.
________________________________________
Step 19: Problem — CrashLoopBackOff
Check pods:
oc get pods
Output:
exoplanets CrashLoopBackOff
Reason:
Pods loaded old secret values.
Pods only read secrets at startup.
________________________________________
Step 20: Restart Pods
Solution:
Restart deployments.
Database restart:
oc rollout restart deployment/database
Application restart:
oc rollout restart deployment/exoplanets
This recreates pods with new configuration.
________________________________________
Step 21: Monitor Pods
Command:
watch oc get pods
New pods appear:
database Running
exoplanets Running
Application works again.
________________________________________
Step 22: View Last Applied Configuration
Command:
oc get deployment exoplanets -o yaml
Inside output you will see:
kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration
Purpose
Tracks the last YAML manifest applied.
This helps oc apply compare:
1.	current resource
2.	last applied config
3.	new manifest
________________________________________
Step 23: Clean Up Resources
Delete application resources:
oc delete -f . --namespace declarative-manifests
Output:
deployment deleted
service deleted
route deleted
________________________________________
Step 24: Finish Lab
Command:
lab finish declarative-manifests
This resets the lab environment.
________________________________________
Complete Workflow Summary
The workflow used in this exercise:
Git Repository
      ↓
Clone YAML manifests
      ↓
Validate manifests
      ↓
oc apply
      ↓
Application deployed
      ↓
Update manifests
      ↓
oc diff
      ↓
oc apply
      ↓
Rolling update
________________________________________
Key Commands You Learned
Command	Purpose
oc login	login to cluster
oc new-project	create namespace
git clone	download manifests
oc apply -f	create/update resources
oc diff	compare live resources vs manifests
oc get pods	view pod status
oc rollout restart	restart deployment
oc delete -f	delete resources

